Objectives

The primary objectives of this analysis is to fit monthly light response curves for Harvard forest to understand annual patterns ecosystem photosynthetic potential and respiration rates in temperate mixed forests of Massachusetts.

Methods

Site Information:

Harvard Forest is a deciduous forest located in Petersham, Massachusetts (42.53,-72.19) with multiple study sites (Figure 1). Harvard forest has a cool and moist temperature with mean seasonal temperatures ranging from -7C to 20C. Temperature and ecosystem phososynthetic data was collected annually from 1991-2016 at long-term study plot, NEON tower (Figure 2).

Discussion

Visualizing the data with a scatter plot shows high variation with an increase in temperature (Figure 3). In order to determine if there was a relationship between temperature (TA) and net ecosystem exchange (NEE), a temperature response curve was fitted (Arrhenius approach: NEE ~ a exp(bTA)). The residuals and autocorrelation graphs plotted in Figure 4 show that the data violate the normality assumption and thus did not fit this model. Therefore, there is no relationship between temperature and net ecosystem exchange.
